Sentiment Analysis Badge

LASER Institute TM Learning Lab 3

Katie McCarthy

July 16, 2022

The final activity for each learning lab provides space to work with data and to reflect on how the concepts and techniques introduced in each lab might apply to your own research.

To earn a badge for each lab, you are required to respond to a set of prompts for two parts:

  • In Part I, you will reflect on your understanding of key concepts and begin to think about potential next steps for your own study.

  • In Part II, you will create a simple data product in R that demonstrates your ability to apply a data analysis technique introduced in this learning lab.

Part I: Reflect and Plan

Use the institutional library (e.g.NCSU Library), Google Scholar or search engine to locate a research article, presentation, or resource that applies text mining to an educational context or topic of interest. More specifically, locate a text mining study that visualize text data.

  1. Provide an APA citation for your selected study.

    • Lemay, D. J., Baek, C., & Doleck, T. (2021). Comparison of learning analytics and educational data mining: A topic modeling approach. Computers and Education: Artificial Intelligence, 2, 100016.

  2. How does topic modeling address research questions?

    • In thinking about George Siemenss keynote, I was interested in the similarities and differences in LA and EDM. The researchers did a literature search from 2015-2019 for the terms Educational Data Mining and Learning Analytics. They used structural topic modeling to for each set of papers to get a sense of the topics in each field. I question, however, that the top words in both were Learning, Analytics, Educational, Data, and Mining. It seems to me that those words (or perhaps the bi-gram and tri-gram respectively should have been removed.)

Draft a research question for a population you may be interested in studying, or that would be of interest to educational researchers, and that would require the collection of text data and answer the following questions:

  1. What text data would need to be collected?
  • I would be interested in examining our graduate student presentations and publications to examine what types of research is conducted in our interdisciplinary department.

  1. For what reason would text data need to be collected in order to address this question?

    • Our formal program distinctions tend to be simplistic and overlapping. Papers and presentations would allow us to examine the intersections of topics and methodologies that students are using to address questions across different learning sciences programs.

  2. Explain the analytical level at which these text data would need to be collected and analyzed.

    • Word level (or bigram level) analysis would help to identify relevant themes across the corpus of papers.

Knit & Submit

Congratulations, youve completed your Intro to text mining Badge! Complete the following steps to submit your work for review:

  1. Change the name of the author: in the YAML header at the very top of this document to your name. As noted in Reproducible Research in R, The YAML header controls the style and feel for knitted document but doesnt actually display in the final output.

  2. Click the yarn icon above to knit your data product to a HTML file that will be saved in your R Project folder.

  3. Commit your changes in GitHub Desktop and push them to your online GitHub repository.

  4. Publish your HTML page the web using one of the following publishing methods:

    • Publish on RPubs by clicking the Publish button located in the Viewer Pane when you knit your document. Note, you will need to quickly create a RPubs account.

    • Publishing on GitHub using either GitHub Pages or the HTML previewer.

  5. Post a new discussion on GitHub to our Text mining Badges forum. In your post, include a link to your published web page and a short reflection highlighting one thing you learned from this lab and one thing youd like to explore further.
